<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-10-09T10:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-10-09T10:00:00-05:00" n="177" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d177">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">511.3B1/6: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Commission to Negotiate
                                    Peace</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-10-09T15:00:00+00:00"><hi rend="italic">October 9,
                                        1919—3 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received October 9—2:28
                                p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>4592. Your 3310, October 2, 2 p.m. Brazil, Honduras and Uruguay did not
                            sign the Arms Traffic Convention as they had no plenipotentiaries in
                            Paris at time of signature. Article 23 of chapter V of the convention
                            however provides for subsequent adherence of states members of the
                            League of Nations. Polk.</p>
                        <closer><hi rend="smallcaps">American Mission</hi></closer>
                    </div>
